defaultHer email contains 
defaultlies about supposed attempts to contact medefault. In her email to me she claimed that she had tried to
default investigate my side of the story, that she tried to contact me during her investigation but found my “whereabouts unknown”. Yet she contradicts herself in the next sentence when she claimed that she had tried to contact me at my employer. Every one of my 
defaultemployers has maintained a web page in the public domain with my profile and full contact details. She claims to have tried to contact me at 
defaultCranfield
default University around the time that she compiled and signed her report in February 2008, but I was not employ
defaulted by 
defaultCranfield
default University until April 2008. She claimed that her emails to me on my employer’s email server were returned, but nobody else had any trouble with that server, including my ex-wife, who defamed me to 
defaultCranfield
default in June 2008. If any email had b
defaultounced, she could have written to me at my employer’s postal address. In any case, I had other public profiles, most obviously on my own business’ website, with publically-accessible email address and postal address, and a dozen other public profiles, incl
